    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey my realtor just mentioned something about needing an escrow account for the house closing in toronto. i've never heard of this before, what actually is escrow and why do i need it for the transaction?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "An escrow account is essentially a neutral third-party vault where funds and documents are held until the closing conditions are met, ensuring neither the buyer nor the seller gets a surprise. In the Toronto real estate market, this is standard practice to protect both parties, especially when dealing with complex financing and title transfers. Without it, you'd be risking your earnest money or the seller's funds, which is why your realtor insists on it.\n\nThink of the escrow agent as a strict, no-nonsense guardian who only releases the keys and the money once everyone has signed the right papers. If you skip this step, the transaction could fall apart, and you might end up with a house that doesn't belong to you or a seller who walks away with nothing. It's a safety net, but it's also a bureaucratic hurdle that requires patience.\n\nJust remember, while you're waiting for the escrow to clear, you're essentially holding your breath while the paperwork gets shuffled around. Once everything is verified, the escrow agent will distribute the funds, and you'll get the deed. It's a necessary evil, but one that keeps the whole deal from turning into a chaotic mess.",
