    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "okay that makes sense. so like who actually holds the money? is it the lawyer or is it some kind of separate company? i'm just worried about where my deposit is sitting while we wait for all the paperwork to finish.",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "The money is typically held in a specialized trust account by a licensed real estate lawyer or a designated escrow agent, not just sitting in a generic business account. In Toronto, the law requires these professionals to keep client funds separate from their own operating accounts to ensure your deposit is secure and traceable. You don't need to worry about the money disappearing; it's locked in a secure vault until the specific conditions of your contract are met.\n\nThink of it like a high-security bank safe that only the lawyer and the escrow agent have the combination to open. If you were to ask a random person to hold your deposit, they might be tempted to use it for their own expenses, but a regulated lawyer or escrow company has to report every single cent they touch to the government. It's a bit more paperwork than you'd expect, but it's the only way to guarantee your funds stay exactly where they belong until the day you sign the final papers.\n\nJust remember, while the money is \"in escrow,\" it's not yours to spend yet, but it's also not gone; it's just on hold. Once the lawyer confirms the title is clear and the financing is approved, they will release the funds to the seller,",
      "source": "target",
